TextData.SourceString:
If this is checked the rig's pose needs to be reset to its initial
prior to evaluating the rig.

If this is checked the bone pose coming from the AnimBP will be
transferred into the Control Rig.

If this is checked the curves coming from the AnimBP will be
transferred into the Control Rig.

Transferring the pose in global space guarantees a global pose match,
while transferring in local space ensures a match of the local transforms.
In general transforms only differ if the hierarchy topology differs
between the Control Rig and the skeleton used in the AnimBP.
Note: Turning this off can potentially improve performance.

An inclusive list of bones to transfer as part
of the input pose transfer phase.
If this list is empty all bones will be transferred.
The customized event queue to run

Tags.string 'NodeComment': The bot has also a physic asset for the ragdoll and to simulate the head when he goes in inactive state. You could extend it with the antennas so they could being simulated and collide with the world.
First we do the Ground locomotion. This contains only a blend space between run and idle. The walk/run uses a blendspace that is set up to use the speed and the lean amount we calculated.

The air locomotion state machine uses the cached GroundLocoPose as start. It is a bit more complicated as we not only jump and fall but also have the jetpack that comes with own animations. So there are several states that can blend into each other. 
The jump start takes the ground speed and a blendspace to blend from an idle to jump to a run to jump. 
Also noticable is the land. There are two transitions. One for MovementInput true and one for false as we have to land animations depending if the character stops after landing or keeps moving. This is a very simple setup but it works in our case quite well.
Now we take that pose and add a slot for an UpperBody animation. This is used in the interact-press-button montage and is triggered when the bot presses a button.
Here we do a blend per bone that defines that the UpperBody slot only affects the bones above the pelvis. He can theoretical press a button while running or flying.
This is maybe not the most elegant solution but with a blend poses by bool we switch to the inactive idle animation. We tweaked the blend time and the result was ok for this case.

This pose now goes into control rig where some magic happens. 
We blend into IK when the feet get close to a surface. 
And we blend into IK when the robot presses a button. 
That InteractWorldLocation went from the button into the interaction component. The pawn got it from there and the event graph here took that value which we now feed into the control rig. But it doesnt have to be a button. You could extend this with a level or any other object the chracter should interact with.
Check out the Control Rig to get more details. 
This pose is what gets output.
The anim graph here tries to seperate the different behaviour in a modular way and cache the poses in each step. It is easier to work isolated on parts of it and it's better for debugging.

We save the current and last last orientation, caclulate the delta and use an Finterp to smooth fast changes. Then we save that to a value we can use in AnimGraph in a blend space to lean left or  right when running.
Here we gather all the data we need to drive the animation
The character component knows if the character is in air and we get the ground speed. We ignore movment in Z here.
Check the function to see how the lean amount is calculated.
The pawn knows the last movement input so we use that to find out if there is currently movement input. We will use this to decide between a hard land or a land that goes into a run.
We need to cast to our BP_Bot to get data. Is he inactive or hovering. At this point it can make sense to make an own enum hl
An animation notify set in the landing animation to do a small shake when robot lands.
